liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Home Affairs Minister Clare O'Neil says another flight leaves Tel Aviv today and is the last planned flight organised by Australian government for people to leave Israel. "This is the last planned flight that the Australian government is supporting out of Israel," the minister told ABC News Breakfast. "It doesn't mean that absolutely there will be no more flights, but what I would say to anyone who is in Israel, if you are planning to leave, please get on this plane." A repatriation flight carrying 252 people, about half of whom were Australian citizens, landed in Sydney early this morning. Ms O'Neil has urged Australians in Israel to leave on this last planned flight. "Don't assume that there will be continuous options to leave. If you want to leave, there is a flight leaving today, please get on it," she said. Forty-six Australians in Gaza have registered with the government to leave the war-torn area. "What we need to understand here is that Gaza is effectively locked off, "There are 2 million people living in a tiny plot of land with only one entry and exit point that is currently not open," she says. Ms O'Neil says the government is trying "incredibly hard" to get more information about the Australians in Gaza and is working on a plan to get them out.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ‘Last planned flight’ by the Australian government leaves Tel Aviv today

children.content: Clare O'Neil says today's flight the last one planned to leave Israel.
(ABC News)
Home Affairs Minister Clare O'Neil says another flight leaves Tel Aviv today and is the last planned flight organised by Australian government for people to leave Israel.
"This is the last planned flight that the Australian government is supporting out of Israel," the minister told ABC News Breakfast.
"It doesn't mean that absolutely there will be no more flights, but what I would say to anyone who is in Israel, if you are planning to leave, please get on this plane."
A repatriation flight carrying 252 people, about half of whom were Australian citizens, landed in Sydney early this morning.
Ms O'Neil has urged Australians in Israel to leave on this last planned flight.
"Don't assume that there will be continuous options to leave. If you want to leave, there is a flight leaving today, please get on it," she said.
Forty-six Australians in Gaza have registered with the government to leave the war-torn area.
"What we need to understand here is that Gaza is effectively locked off,
"There are 2 million people living in a tiny plot of land with only one entry and exit point that is currently not open," she says.
Ms O'Neil says the government is trying "incredibly hard" to get more information about the Australians in Gaza and is working on a plan to get them out.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: US President Joe Biden says Egyptian President Abdel Fattah al-Sisi has agreed to open the Rafah Crossing to allow about 20 trucks carrying humanitarian aid into Gaza. "Sisi deserves some real credit because he was accommodating," Mr Biden said, according to the Reuters news agency. Israel's government says it won't stop aid from entering Gaza from Egypt, but the supplies won't be allowed to reach Palestinian militant group Hamas. "Israel will not prevent humanitarian assistance from Egypt as long as it is only food, water and medicine for the civilian population located in the southern Gaza Strip or (those) evacuating to there, and as long as these supplies do not reach Hamas," the office of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu says. Israel said it made the decision after a request from Biden, but added that it would continue its blockade of humanitarian aid from Israel into Gaza "as long as our hostages are not returned". Egypt has been stockpiling aid on its side of the border, but trucks have been unable to cross amid Israel's airstrikes in its war with Hamas.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Joe Biden says Egypt has agreed to allow humanitarian aid into Gaza

Israel said it made the decision after a request from Biden, but added that it would continue its blockade of humanitarian aid from Israel into Gaza "as long as our hostages are not returned".
Egypt has been stockpiling aid on its side of the border, but trucks have been unable to cross amid Israel's airstrikes in its war with Hamas.
